'''Thomas Christiansen Tarín'''{{efn|{{IPA|da|ˈtsʰʌmæs kʰʁeˈstjænˀsn̩ tsʰɑˈʁin, - kʰʁæˈ-|lang|small=no}}, {{IPA|es|ˈtomas kɾisˈtjansen taˈɾin|lang|small=no}}.}} (born 11 March 1973) is a [[Association football|football]] [[Manager (association football)|manager]] and former player who played as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]]. He is the current [[Manager (association football)|manager]] of the [[Panama national football team|Panama national team]].

He played for a number of clubs in Denmark, Spain and Germany in a 15-year professional career, being crowned top scorer of the [[2002–03 Bundesliga]] while with [[VfL Bochum|Bochum]]. Born in Denmark, he represented the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]], earning two [[Cap (sport)|caps]] in 1993.

In 2013, Christiansen started working as a manager. He led [[Panama national football team|Panama]] at two [[CONCACAF Gold Cup]]s, finishing as runners-up in [[2023 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2023]].

==Playing career==
===Early years===
Born in [[Hadsund]] in Denmark to a [[Spaniards|Spanish]] mother, Christiansen was raised in [[Copenhagen]].<ref name=BT>{{cite news|title=Cruyffs nye stjerneskud Thomas fra Hvidovre|trans-title=Cruyff's newest star from Hvidovre|newspaper=[[BT (tabloid)|BT]]|first=Steen|last=Uno|language=da|date=4 July 1991}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+TOP+TO+BOCHUM%3B+Dane+from+Spain+Thomas+gives+new+boys+dream...-a090741473|title=Football: Top to Bochum; Dane from Spain Thomas gives new boys dream start|publisher=The Free Library|date=26 August 2002|access-date=31 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parikiaki.com/2014/06/aek-larnaca-make-sixth-signing/|title=AEK Larnaca make sixth signing|publisher=Parikiaki|date=18 June 2014|access-date=31 July 2014}}</ref> He started playing football aged nine in [[Avedøre IF|Avedøre]], then spent one year at [[Brøndby IF|Brøndby]] before moving on to [[Hvidovre IF|Hvidovre]].

Christiansen trained with the youth team of [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]], but when his mother forbade him to join the club, he moved to [[Boldklubben af 1893|B.93]].<ref name=BT/> In May 1991, he scored six goals in a youth team match against [[Kjøbenhavns Boldklub|KB]], and went back to Spain to train with [[1990–91 La Liga|defending]] [[La Liga]] champions [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pingel bliver den næste|trans-title=Pingel will be the next|newspaper=[[Berlingske]]|first=Jens-Carl|last=Kristensen|language=da|date=30 June 1991}}</ref>

===Barcelona===
Christiansen signed a four-year contract with Barcelona in July 1991, when [[Johan Cruyff]] was team manager, with a dream of playing alongside their Danish [[playmaker]] [[Michael Laudrup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Drømmen er at spille med Laudrup|trans-title=Dream of playing with Laudrup|newspaper=[[Ekstra Bladet]]|language=da|date=31 July 1991}}</ref> He started competing as a senior with [[FC Barcelona Atlètic|the reserves]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/deportes/futbol/20110302/54121008032/jonathan-soriano-se-convierte-en-el-maximo-goleador-de-la-historia-del-filial.html|title=Jonathan Soriano se convierte en el máximo goleador de la historia del filial|trans-title=Jonathan Soriano becomes the highest goalscorer in the history of the reserves|newspaper=[[La Vanguardia]]|language=es|date=2 March 2011|access-date=6 November 2019}}</ref> where he soon was joined by compatriot [[Ronnie Ekelund]]; during this period, he was frequently called up to train with the main squad, but received almost no playing time due to stiff competition.<ref name=SS>{{cite web|url=https://www.spherasports.com/thomas-christiansen-entre-contrastes-y-azares/|title=Thomas Christiansen, entre contrastes y azares|trans-title=Thomas Christiansen, between contrasts and jinxes|publisher=Sphera Sports|first=Juanma|last=Perera|language=es|date=25 October 2016|access-date=21 June 2024}}</ref>

When he joined Barcelona, Christiansen agreed to a clause in his contract that stated he would be a [[Spanish nationality law|Spanish citizen]], and thereby not count towards the foreigner quota in the league. After becoming naturalised, he was called up for the [[Spain national under-21 football team|under-21 team]] in December 1992,<ref>{{cite news|title=Thomas på spansk landshold|trans-title=Thomas with Spanish national team|newspaper=BT|first=Peter Juul|last=Madsen|language=da|date=14 December 1992}}</ref> and scored a goal to help defeat [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany]] 2–1.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1992/12/16/pagina-55/1254769/pdf.html|title=Los sub-21 de Goikoetxea ganan a Alemania por 1–2|trans-title=Goikoetxea's under-21 defeat Germany 1–2|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|language=es|date=16 December 1992|access-date=20 December 2014}}</ref>

Still playing for Barcelona's B team, Christiansen was called up for the [[Spain national football team|Spain senior squad]] by manager [[Javier Clemente]], in January 1993, making his debut against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] on the 27th and impressing in a game which featured few regulars for the European nation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1993/01/28/pagina-15/1264280/pdf.html|title=Más joven, pero igual de gris|trans-title=Younger, but just as grey|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Rogelio|last=Román|language=es|date=28 January 1993|access-date=20 December 2014}}</ref> He prolonged his link with the [[Catalonia|Catalans]] until 1997, and made his official debut for the club on 10 February when he played the last seven minutes of the [[UEFA Super Cup]] [[1992 European Super Cup|final]] – first leg – away to [[SV Werder Bremen|Werder Bremen]].<ref name=MD>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1993/02/11/pagina-2/1275596/pdf.html|title=El Barça encarrila otro euro-título|trans-title=Barça all but win another euro-title|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Jesús|last=Galindo|language=es|date=11 February 1993|access-date=20 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1993/02/11/pagina-7/1275600/pdf.html|title=Christiansen: "Al fin he cumplido mi gran sueño"|trans-title=Christiansen: "Finally my big dream has come true"|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Jesús|last=Galindo|language=es|date=11 February 1993|access-date=20 December 2014}}</ref> His final competitive appearance took place in a [[Copa del Rey]] tie against [[Atlético Madrid]] one week later,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vavel.com/es/futbol/2017/02/01/fc-barcelona/749740-la-contundente-eliminacion-del-barcelona-al-atletico-de-1993.html|title=La contundente eliminación del Barcelona al Atlético de 1993|trans-title=Barcelona's forceful elimination of Atlético of 1993|publisher=[[Vavel]]|first=Joan|last=Cloquell|language=es|date=1 February 2017|access-date=10 July 2025}}</ref> and was once more selected to the national team, appearing as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a [[1994 FIFA World Cup]] [[1994 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualifier]] against [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]] and scoring with a flick of the heel in an eventual 5–0 home win.<ref name=INTGOAL>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1993/02/25/pagina-2/1270413/pdf.html|title=La selección repite otro 5–0 en Sevilla|trans-title=The national team repeat another 5–0 in Seville|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Alberto|last=Sanchis|language=es|date=25 February 1993|access-date=20 December 2014}}</ref>

Without having played any league games for Barcelona, Christiansen was put [[Loan (sports)|on loan]] at fellow top-division club [[Sporting de Gijón]], in February 1993. He was mostly injured during that stint, but managed four league goals, subsequently returning to the [[Camp Nou]] where he suffered another injury during pre-season;<ref>{{cite news|title=Jeg vil spille for Cruyff|trans-title=I want to play for Cruyff|newspaper=Ekstra Bladet|first=Frits|last=Ahlstrøm|language=da|date=30 October 1994}}</ref> other loans followed, first at [[CA Osasuna|Osasuna]] then at [[Racing de Santander]] in the [[1994–95 La Liga|1994–95 season]], starting well enough at the latter to earn another call-up by Spain, only to pull out due to injury.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://blogs.20minutos.es/quefuede/2008/01/02/quao-fue-de-christiansen/|title=Qué fue de… Christiansen|trans-title=What happened to… Christiansen|newspaper=[[20 minutos]]|first=Edu|last=Casado|language=es|date=2 January 2008|access-date=21 June 2024}}</ref>

===Mixed success===
Spanish league regulations stated that following three years of loan contracts, Barcelona had to compensate Christiansen financially, if they declined any proposed [[Transfer (association football)|transfer deal]]. He was first sold to English club [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in October 1995, but wanted to stay in Spain, being instead transferred to [[Real Oviedo]] the next January for [[Danish krone|DKK]] 4.6&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|title=Oviedo scorer mål- sluger|trans-title=|newspaper=BT|first=Jørgen|last=Pihl|language=da|date=7 January 1996}}</ref> Following a good start, he failed to score any goals in his [[1996–97 La Liga|second year]] even though he appeared in 31 matches, and was sold to [[Segunda División]]'s [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] in November 1997, helping them [[1997–98 Segunda División|promote]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.revistapoble.net/2018/06/12/20-anos-despues-el-reencuentro-de-la-plantilla-del-primer-ascenso-del-villarreal-cf-a-primera-division/|title=20 años después: el reencuentro de la plantilla del primer ascenso del Villarreal CF a Primera División|trans-title=20 years later: the Villarreal CF squad of the first promotion to ''Primera División'' meet again|publisher=Revista Poble|language=es|date=12 June 2018|access-date=21 June 2024}}</ref> but managing to find the net only once the [[1998–99 La Liga|following campaign]], which ended in relegation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.revistapoble.net/24-imatges-centenari-villarreal/|title=100 anys en 24 imatges en groc|trans-title=100 years in 24 pictures in yellow|publisher=Revista Poble|language=es|date=2023|access-date=21 June 2024}}</ref>

A proposed deal with a Mexican team never materialised, and Christiansen was without a club in 1999. He went on to play for [[Terrassa FC|Terrassa]] in the Spanish lower leagues,<ref>{{cite news|title=En stjerne i mørket|trans-title=A star in the dark|publisher=Aktuelt|language=da|date=30 October 1999}}</ref> finishing that season at [[Panionios F.C.|Panionios]] in Greece before returning to Denmark in August 2000, signing with defending [[Danish Superliga|Danish champions]] [[Herfølge BK|Herfølge]], and showing good form when he scored two goals in a win over [[2000–01 Danish Superliga|eventual runners-up]] Brøndby.

===Breakthrough in Germany===
In January 2001, Christiansen moved to Germany to play for [[VfL Bochum]] in the [[Bundesliga]], [[2000–01 Bundesliga|being relegated]] to the [[2. Bundesliga|second division]] (as with Herfølge) but contributing 17 goals [[2001–02 2. Bundesliga|the following season]] to be the [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]'s team top scorer as they won promotion; he added 21 in [[2002–03 Bundesliga|next year's top flight]], being crowned joint league top scorer with [[Giovane Élber]] of [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]].<ref name=SPOX>{{cite web|url=http://www.spox.com/de/sport/fussball/bundesliga/1705/Artikel/torjaeger-torschuetzenkoenig-2017.html|title=Aubameyang ist Torschützenkönig 2017|trans-title=Aubameyang is 2017 top scorer|publisher=Spox|language=de|date=20 May 2017|access-date=22 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rsssf.org/players/tchristiansendata.html|title=Thomas CHRISTIANSEN Tarín – Matches and Goals in Bundesliga|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|first=Matthias|last=Arnhold|access-date=9 May 2011}}</ref>

Following that achievement, Christiansen was signed by [[Hannover 96]] in June 2003 to replace [[Fredi Bobic]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/sport/fussball-bundesliga-hannover-96-christiansen-ersetzt-bobic-11326848.html|title=Hannover 96: Christiansen ersetzt Bobic|trans-title=Hannover 96: Christiansen replaces Bobic|newspaper=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]]|language=de|date=6 June 2003|access-date=3 June 2020}}</ref> He scored nine times in his [[2003–04 Bundesliga|first year]], but failed to reproduce his previous form mainly due to several injuries, including a knee operation and two [[shinbone]] ailments; in the summer of 2006, the club chose not to prolong his contract and he left, retiring shortly after at the age of 33.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reviersport.de/fussball/1bundesliga/a213540---50-jahre-bl-thomas-christiansen-interview.html|title="Bochum war wie eine Familie"|trans-title="Bochum were like a family"|publisher=Revier Sport|first=Kristina|last=Jäger|language=de|date=10 November 2012|access-date=21 June 2024}}</ref><ref name=SS/>

==Coaching career==
===Early spells and AEK===
Christiansen started his managerial career in the [[United Arab Emirates]], as part of [[Luis Milla (footballer, born 1966)|Luis Milla]]'s coaching staff at [[Al Jazira Club|Al Jazira]], arriving in February 2013 and leaving in October as the latter was fired. In late April 2014 he was appointed head coach of [[AEK Larnaca FC|AEK Larnaca]] in the [[Cypriot First Division]], after having been approached for the job by former Barcelona B teammate [[Xavier Roca]], who acted as [[director of football]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aek.com.cy/link.php?id=2387|title=Συμβόλαιο συνεργασίας με Thomas Christiansen|trans-title=Cooperation contract with Thomas Christiansen|publisher=AEK Larnaca|language=el|date=30 April 2014|access-date=1 May 2014}}{{dead link|date=January 2018|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> in his first two seasons, he led them to consecutive best-ever runner-up league finishes.<ref name=LEEDS>{{cite web|url=https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/21967/head-coach-appointed|title=Head coach appointed|publisher=Leeds United F.C.|date=15 June 2017|access-date=15 June 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170615152703/https://www.leedsunited.com/news/team-news/21967/head-coach-appointed|archive-date=15 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfa.com.cy/Gr/news/22530/1762710/159|title=ΑΠΟΕΛ&nbsp;– ΑΕΚ 1–1 (video)|trans-title=ΑPΟΕL&nbsp;– ΑΕΚ 1–1 (video)|publisher=[[Cyprus Football Association]]|language=el|date=16 May 2015|access-date=11 November 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150524234726/http://www.cfa.com.cy/Gr/news/22530/1762710/159|archive-date=24 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfa.com.cy/Gr/news/22618|script-title=el:Η τελική κατάταξη|trans-title=The final ranking|publisher=Cyprus Football Association|language=el|date=24 May 2015|access-date=11 November 2015}}</ref>

Also during the [[2015–16 Cypriot First Division|2015–16 campaign]], Christiansen coached his team to the [[2015–16 UEFA Europa League|third qualifying round]] of the [[UEFA Europa League]], losing 4–0 on aggregate to [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ouest-france.fr/sport/football/ligue-europa-realiste-bordeaux-gagne-et-se-qualifie-3606200/amp|title=Ligue Europa. Très efficace, Bordeaux se qualifie pour les barrages|trans-title=Europa League. Highly effective, Bordeaux qualify to playoffs|newspaper=[[Ouest-France]]|language=fr|date=6 August 2015|access-date=21 June 2017}}</ref>

===APOEL===
On 21 May 2016, after two successful seasons, Christiansen moved to reigning Cypriot champions [[APOEL FC|APOEL]], signing a one-year contract effective as of 1 June.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apoelfc.com.cy/nqcontent.cfm?a_id=15100&tt=graphic&lang=l1|title=Σύναψη συμφωνίας με τον προπονητή Thomas Christiansen|trans-title=Agreement with coach Thomas Christiansen|publisher=APOEL FC|language=el|date=21 May 2016|access-date=21 May 2016|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629133738/http://apoelfc.com.cy/nqcontent.cfm?a_id=15100&tt=graphic&lang=l1|archive-date=29 June 2016}}</ref> On 2 August, they knocked out [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]] 4–1 on aggregate in the [[2016–17 UEFA Champions League|third qualifying round]] of the [[UEFA Champions League]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/match/2020352--apoel-vs-rosenborg/|title=APOEL 3–0 Rosenborg|publisher=UEFA|date=2 August 2016|access-date=15 June 2017}}</ref> being ousted the following stage by [[F.C. Copenhagen|Copenhagen]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/0230-0e94a656cb37-d5a156ce53ff-1000--champions-league-play-off-draw-made/|title=Champions League play-off draw made|publisher=UEFA|date=5 August 2016|access-date=15 June 2017}}</ref> and eventually reaching the [[2016–17 UEFA Europa League|last-16 in the Europa League]] for the first time in their history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/0234-0e95e11a50ba-3e41dfd810be-1000--uefa-europa-league-round-of-32-draw/|title=UEFA Europa League round of 32 draw|publisher=UEFA|date=12 December 2016|access-date=15 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/0236-0e96584867af-aaa573df647f-1000--gladbach-anderlecht-celta-and-lyon-take-headlines/|title=Gladbach, Anderlecht, Celta and Lyon take headlines|publisher=UEFA|date=23 February 2017|access-date=15 June 2017}}</ref>

Christiansen won his first managerial title in 2017 after [[2016–17 Cypriot First Division|conquering the Cypriot League]], losing only two games during the season and having the best defensive record with 27 [[Shutout#Association football|clean sheets]].<ref name=CL>{{cite news|url=http://cyprus-mail.com/2017/05/13/apoel-seal-title-win-arch-rivals-omonia/|title=Apoel seal title after win over arch-rivals Omonia|newspaper=[[Cyprus Mail]]|first=Iacovos|last=Constantinou|date=13 May 2017|access-date=15 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=EVENING>{{cite news|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/thomas-christiansen-new-leeds-united-head-coach-s-managerial-career-in-focus-1-8597680|title=Thomas Christiansen: New Leeds United head coach's managerial career in focus|newspaper=[[Yorkshire Evening Post]]|date=15 June 2017|access-date=15 June 2017}}</ref> He also reached [[2016–17 Cypriot Cup|the final]] of [[Cypriot Cup|the domestic cup]], lost 1–0 to [[Apollon Limassol FC|Apollon Limassol]];<ref name=CC>{{cite news|url=http://cyprus-mail.com/2017/05/24/ten-man-apollon-defeat-apoel-win-cyprus-cup/|title=Ten-man Apollon defeat Apoel to win Cyprus Cup|newspaper=Cyprus Mail|first=Andreas|last=Vou|date=24 May 2017|access-date=22 June 2017}}</ref> on 25 May a meeting between club and coach was held, and subsequently both decided to part ways.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apoelfc.com.cy/nqcontent.cfm?a_id=16260&tt=graphic&lang=l1|title=Μη ανανέωση συνεργασίας με Thomas Christiansen|trans-title=Partnership with Thomas Christiansen not renewed|publisher=APOEL FC|language=el|date=25 May 2016|access-date=25 May 2016}}</ref>

===Leeds United===
On 15 June 2017, Christiansen was announced as the new head coach of [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40287680|title=Thomas Christiansen: Leeds United name ex-Spain international as head coach|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=15 June 2017|access-date=15 June 2017}}</ref> after being appointed by new owner [[Andrea Radrizzani]] to replace [[Garry Monk]], with the club announcing that they wanted "to appoint someone who can help us create a winning culture at the club and unite everyone connected with Leeds United, from the players to the supporters".<ref name=LEEDS/><ref name=EVENING/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united-unknown-dane-christiansen-get-radrizzanis-blessing-644913|title=Leeds United: Unknown Dane Christiansen get Radrizzani's blessing|newspaper=Yorkshire Evening Post|date=15 June 2017|access-date=15 June 2017}}</ref> Four days later, it was revealed that he would be joined by assistant [[Julio Bañuelos]], fitness coach Iván Torres and goalkeeper coach [[Marcos Abad]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.leedsunited.com/video/86973/thomas-christiansen-the-first-press-conference|title=Thomas Christiansen &#124; The first press conference|publisher=Leeds United F.C.|date=19 June 2017|access-date=19 June 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802171826/https://www.leedsunited.com/video/86973/thomas-christiansen-the-first-press-conference|archive-date=2 August 2017}}</ref>

Christiansen was dismissed on 4 February 2018, after a poor run of results and with the team [[2017–18 EFL Championship|tenth in the table]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42940326|title=Leeds dismiss manager Thomas Christiansen after eight months|publisher=BBC Sport|date=4 February 2018|access-date=4 February 2018}}</ref>

===Union SG===
On 1 July 2019, Christiansen was appointed at [[Belgian First Division B]]'s [[Royale Union Saint-Gilloise|Union SG]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20190701_04488391|title=Thomas Christiansen is de nieuwe trainer van Union Sint-Gillis: "Blij dat we iemand met zo'n cv konden aanwerven"|trans-title=Thomas Christiansen is the new manager of Union Saint-Gilloise: "Glad we could recruit someone with such a résumé"|newspaper=[[Het Nieuwsblad]]|language=nl|date=1 July 2019|access-date=1 July 2019}}</ref> He was released in May 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rusg.brussels/article/thomas-christiansen-fin-de-la-collaboration|title=Thomas Christiansen: Fin de la collaboration.|trans-title=Thomas Christiansen: End of cooperation.|publisher=Royale Union Saint-Gilloise|language=fr|date=May 2020|access-date=23 May 2020}}</ref>

===Panama===
Christiansen was named new manager of the [[Panama national football team|Panama national team]] on 23 July 2020, replacing [[Américo Gallego]] who was released amid a restructuring of the [[Panamanian Football Federation]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/internacional/20200723/482476419518/thomas-christiansen-nuevo-seleccionador-de-panama.html|title=Thomas Christiansen, nuevo seleccionador de Panamá|trans-title=Thomas Christiansen, new Panama national team manager|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Jordi|last=Archs|language=es|date=23 July 2020|access-date=31 July 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.qatarnews.net/news/265875109/ex-spain-forward-christiansen-takes-charge-of-panama|title=Ex-Spain forward Christiansen takes charge of Panama|newspaper=Qatar News|date=24 July 2020|access-date=31 July 2020}}</ref> His first games were [[Exhibition game|friendlies]] away to neighbours [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]] on 10 and 13 October, both won by a single [[Abdiel Ayarza]] goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rpctv.com/marea-roja/thomas-christiansen-y-su-retorno-costa-rica-donde-todo-comenzo-n5651408|title=Thomas Christiansen y su retorno a Costa Rica, donde todo comenzó|trans-title=Thomas Christiansen and his return to Costa Rica, where it all began|publisher=[[RPC Televisión]]|language=es|date=26 January 2022|access-date=9 June 2022}}</ref>

At the [[2021 CONCACAF Gold Cup]], Christiansen's team were eliminated from the group stage after failing to beat [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]] and [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/recap-panama-3-grenada-1|title=Recap: Panama 3, Grenada 1|publisher=[[Major League Soccer]]|first=Ari|last=Liljenwall|date=21 July 2021|access-date=9 June 2022}}</ref> The [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|qualification campaign]] was ended by a 5–1 defeat to the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]] in the penultimate fixture.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.laprensa.hn/deportes/las-lagrimas-de-thomas-christiansen-eliminacion-de-panama-mundial-de-qatar-2022-goleada-estados-unidos-EM6860350|title=Las lágrimas de Thomas Christiansen tras la eliminación de Panamá del Mundial de Qatar 2022|trans-title=Thomas Christiansen's tears after Panama's elimination from the 2022 World Cup in Qatar|newspaper=[[La Prensa (Honduras)|La Prensa]]|language=es|date=27 March 2022|access-date=9 June 2022}}</ref>

Christiansen's Panama came fourth at the [[CONCACAF Nations League]] finals in [[2023 CONCACAF Nations League Finals|2023]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/soccer/2023/07/15/gold-cup-mexico-panama-final-lozano-christiansen/9eba8234-2328-11ee-8994-4b2d0b694a34_story.html|title=Mexico seeks a Gold Cup championship against Panama in redemption tour after disappointing World Cup|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=16 July 2023|access-date=27 July 2023}}</ref> Later in June and July at the [[2023 CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]], they won on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]] against hosts the United States in the semi-finals in [[San Diego]], but lost the [[2023 CONCACAF Gold Cup final|final]] to Mexico by a single goal.<ref name=Mexico>{{cite news|url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20230717-gimenez-the-hero-as-mexico-down-panama-1-0-to-lift-9th-gold-cup|title=Gimenez the hero as Mexico down Panama 1-0 to lift 9th Gold Cup|publisher=[[France 24]]|date=17 July 2023|access-date=27 July 2023}}</ref>

On 23 March 2025, Christiansen took the side to the [[2025 CONCACAF Nations League final|CONCACAF Nations League final]], losing 2–1 against Mexico due to a 93rd-minute [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]].<ref name=CNL>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/mexico-beat-panama-with-stoppage-time-penalty-concacaf-nations-league-title-2025-03-24/#:~:text=March%2023%20(Reuters)%20%2D%20Raul,Inglewood%2C%20California%2C%20on%20Sunday.|title=Mexico beat Panama with stoppage-time penalty for CONCACAF Nations League title|publisher=[[Reuters]]|first1=Frank|last1=Pingue|first2=Christian|last2=Schmollinger|date=23 March 2025|access-date=26 March 2025}}</ref> On 16 June, in the 5–2 win over [[Guadeloupe national football team|Guadeloupe]] in the [[2025 CONCACAF Gold Cup|Gold Cup]] opener, he became the coach with the most matches in Panama history with 73, surpassing [[Hernán Darío Gómez]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.midiario.com/deportivas/record-y-goleada-christiansen-lidera-la-nueva-era-dorada-de-panama/|title=¡Récord y goleada! Christiansen lidera la nueva era dorada de Panamá|trans-title=Record and rout! Christiansen leads Panama's new golden age|newspaper=[[Mi Diario]]|first=Luis|last=Del Valle|language=es|date=17 June 2025|access-date=10 July 2025}}</ref>

On 18 November 2025, following a 3–0 victory against [[El Salvador national football team|El Salvador]], Christiansen [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|qualified the nation]] for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup|following year's World Cup]], their second appearance ever in [[FIFA World Cup|the tournament]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://remezcla.com/culture/panama-becomes-only-central-american-team-to-qualify-for-fifa-2026-world-cup/|title=Panama becomes only Central American team to qualify for FIFA 2026 World Cup|publisher=[[Remezcla]]|first=Lissete|last=Lanuza Sáenz|date=19 November 2025|access-date=20 November 2025}}</ref>

